    "analysis": "From the previous results we see a clear hotspot at ts-travel2-service (high CPU, high trace durations and row_count) inside the incident window. However, the diagnosis rules require the final root-cause to be chosen from the provided candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). We must therefore verify whether any of those candidate services show metric anomalies during the incident window using proper global thresholds (calculated on the full series for each component-KPI) before concluding. The next step is to compute global thresholds (P50 and P95) for each KPI of each candidate component using the full metric series, then filter the metric points to the incident window (2024-01-24 14:22:25 → 2024-01-24 14:52:25 UTC) and count how many in-window points exceed the global P95 (i.e., anomalies). We will use these counts plus earliest anomaly timestamps and in-window maxima to identify which candidate(s) are faulty and to proceed to trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate components [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service], process metric.csv as follows (use the full available series in metric.csv to compute thresholds before any time filtering):\n1) Group by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute: count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P50(value), P95(value) across the full series. These are the global thresholds.\n2) Filter the same metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 14:22:25 → 2024-01-24 14:52:25 UTC and compute for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name): window_count (number of points in window), window_anomaly_count (number of points with value >= global P95), window_max (maximum value in-window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the earliest timestamp in-window where value >= global P95, or null if none).\n3) Return a compact table (limit to top 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p50, p95, window_count, window_anomaly_count, window_max, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Sort by window_anomaly_count descending then by cmdb_id.\nDo not print raw full time series. Ensure thresholds are computed on full series before filtering to the incident window."
}

{
    "analysis": "You have already computed global thresholds for metrics and inspected metric anomalies in the incident window. Key results: ts-travel-service shows multiple resource/latency KPIs exceeding their global P95 (mem, socket, workload, latency) with earliest exceedances between 14:28 and 14:45 UTC; ts-auth-service shows two CPU and two diskio exceedances ~14:27–14:28; many `error` KPIs had p95==0 and should be treated as artifacts. The next step, per the workflow, is trace analysis to decide which of the candidate services is the most likely root-cause service (the rules say use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service when multiple service-level faults exist). We must compute global thresholds on trace features for the candidate components before filtering to the incident window, then look for trace anomalies (e.g., duration_mean or duration_p95 increases, row_count drops or spikes) inside the window. This will help decide whether ts-travel-service or ts-auth-service (or another candidate) is the downstream faulty service linked to the observed metric anomalies.",
