    "instruction": "For the candidate components [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service], analyze trace.csv as follows (compute thresholds on the full trace series first):\n1) Group trace.csv by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute full-series count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P50(value), P95(value).\n2) Filter the trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 14:22:25 → 2024-01-24 14:52:25 UTC and for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: window_count, window_anomaly_count (number of points with value >= global P95), window_max, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (earliest in-window timestamp where value >= global P95, null if none).\n3) Return a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p50, p95, window_count, window_anomaly_count, window_max, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Sort by window_anomaly_count descending then cmdb_id. Do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "You ran trace analysis for the candidate services and discovered that most returned trace series for those candidates were error_rate metrics with global P95 == 0, producing misleading \"anomalies\" (every zero >= 0). That confirms there are no non-zero error spikes in traces for the candidates. From earlier metric analysis, ts-travel-service has multiple KPIs (latency, mem, socket, workload) exceeding global P95 twice in-window, and ts-auth-service has two CPU/diskio exceedances ~14:27–14:28. However, trace-level error rates do not help discriminate the real downstream faulty service because of the zero-P95 artifact. To apply the rules (use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service among multiple faulty services), we now need to analyze trace duration and row_count series (not error_rate) for the candidate services to see which candidate shows trace latency or throughput anomalies in-window. This will help decide whether ts-travel-service or ts-auth-service (or another candidate) is the downstream faulty service. No logs show error_count > 0 so log analysis is unlikely to override metrics/traces findings.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, for the candidate services [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service] do the following (compute thresholds on the full trace series before time filtering):\n1) Select only trace_name that contain 'duration' or 'row_count' (case-insensitive).\n2) Group by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute full-series count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P50(value), P95(value).\n3) Filter to the incident window 2024-01-24 14:22:25 → 2024-01-24 14:52:25 UTC and for each group compute: window_count, window_anomaly_count (value >= global P95), window_max, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first in-window timestamp where value >= global P95, or null).\n4) Return a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p50, p95, window_count, window_anomaly_count, window_max, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Sort by window_anomaly_count descending then cmdb_id. Do not print full time series."
}

